<p>
<p>The linear relationship between two quantitative variables is investigated by using a simple linear regression analysis in a sample of 30 persons. The researcher wants to use an <span class="math inline">\(\alpha\)</span> level of 0.01.</p>
<p>Which critical <em>t</em>-value fits the two-sided test for the linear relationship?</p>
</p>]]></text>
</questiontext>
<generalfeedback format="html">
<text><![CDATA[<p>
<p>In the simple regression model two parameters are estimated: intercept and regression coefficient. Therefore <span class="math inline">\(df = n-2\)</span>. In this case <span class="math inline">\(df = 30-2 = 28\)</span>. For a two-sided test with an <span class="math inline">\(\alpha\)</span>-level of 0.01, fits a right-sided exceedance probability of: <span class="math inline">\(\frac{0.01}{2} = 0.005\)</span>. The <em>t</em>-table shows the corresponding value at <span class="math inline">\(df = 28\)</span> and <span class="math inline">\(t._{005}\)</span>.</p>
<p>This value is 2.763.</p>
</p>]]></text>
</generalfeedback>
